                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "Some people still see it as a success. A while ago (maybe a year or so), I listened to a podcast interview with Peter Wang, well-known in the scientific Python universe for being one of the founders of Anaconda. He summarized the history of Python in science and pointed out the enormous success of a project started by a few young scientists which ended up supporting large-scale projects such as PyTorch. Well, I was one of those young scientists, and I don't see the conversion of scientific Python into a corporate-backed project as a success. In this case, the issue is not lack of financial contribution, but project dominance by two corporations, under whose influence scientific Python has become unsuitable for small-scale research because of the high cost of living with its tech churn."
                            }
